<paragraph id="7FB15FC632F452FED9FB5210B9B18924" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<taxonomicName id="214BFEB5328BDB246CF4C8D11C7FC9AE" class="Arachnida" family="Hypochthoniidae" genus="Hypochthoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">HYPOCHTHONIIDAE Berlese</taxonomicName>
, 1910
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="298ED3C8F8AA101B899C38F1C392EFD8" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="BDC0DF61A5F5EB9AABF8EB98FFD2BCDF" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
In his early publications Berlese (1896a, 1896b) regarded the genus 
<taxonomicName id="AA6D02C8733BE38F72FEBA7D63710D34" class="Arachnida" family="Hypochthoniidae" genus="Hypochthonius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hypochthonius</taxonomicName>
as part of the family 
<taxonomicName id="24944C8E7049A29A8C09ACA97CC1E8BA" class="Arachnida" family="Nothridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Nothridae</taxonomicName>
in which it had a separate Position because of the divided notogaster. The genus consisted of species that are now regarded as representatives of separate families, although (with one exception) these still belong to a single group (
<taxonomicName id="F4CE5F5D85A212C86588D595540CEC8B" infraOrder="Enarthronota" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rank="infraOrder">Enarthronota</taxonomicName>
). Due to the erroneous Observation of a subdivision of the notogaster, Berlese (1896) described also a strongly different species as a 
<taxonomicName id="BCB7FCAE7FC66AD4578B1E14011C31B7" class="Arachnida" family="Hypochthoniidae" genus="Hypochthonius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hypochthonius</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="A5746C8E7AFD17F58A45B67C320AD990" class="Arachnida" family="Hypochthoniidae" genus="Hypochthonius" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tectorum">H. tectorum</taxonomicName>
); this species (afterwards the type of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="40919CD6EA71FBF6B59A028985FBBE37" class="Arachnida" family="Trhypochthoniidae" genus="Trhypochthonius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Trhypochthonius</taxonomicName>
) shows, however, little relationship with the 
<taxonomicName id="9E327F4A484495ED75B3B3E8EA595183" infraOrder="Enarthronota" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rank="infraOrder">Enarthronota</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4E5B5A2F0A278880F687ED498A04ED73" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
In 1910 (p. 218) Berlese created a family 
<taxonomicName id="5121FB0E2C639C72312CDE9E8E657E75" family="Hypoctonidae" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rank="family">Hypoctonidae</taxonomicName>
(sic!) 3); he divided the genus 
<taxonomicName id="B140901EAD0E9B2B291E64F5E447D81D" class="Arachnida" family="Hypochthoniidae" genus="Hypochthonius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hypochthonius</taxonomicName>
, and added other genera so that the family in his opinion consisted of 
<taxonomicName id="4E1BD8DC29F884EE356CE1807FD5DB07" class="Arachnida" family="Parhypochthoniidae" genus="Parhypochthonius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Parhypochthonius</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="82CDA6E272403171223D06489FEC4B6C" class="Arachnida" family="Trhypochthoniidae" genus="Trhypochthonius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Trhypochthonius</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="DECC8D4B0424E2334C8C8F2F98CB1E29" class="Arachnida" family="Trizetidae" genus="Trizetes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Trizetes</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="EC6B5BB88F7C2AFDCA268CB2FA8FB59D" class="Arachnida" family="Sphaerochthoniidae" genus="Sphaerochthonius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Sphaerochthonius</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="EFC60CAF4E1264094D438EAC57F78067" class="Arachnida" family="Cosmochthoniidae" genus="Cosmochthonius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Cosmochthonius</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="1E43AB982E0D21F26B1FC00017831797" class="Arachnida" family="Hypochthoniidae" genus="Hypochthonius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hypochthonius</taxonomicName>
(with subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="AEE664384EE86BD33589A9D4B20D361E" class="Arachnida" family="Hypochthoniidae" genus="Hypochthonius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Hypochthoniella">Hypochthoniella</taxonomicName>
), and 
<taxonomicName id="2C3D0918835D199B7094ED2A8DE4422E" class="Arachnida" family="Brachychthoniidae" genus="Brachychthonius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Brachychthonius</taxonomicName>
. Some years after, he gave the same classification (Berlese, 1913a, p. 7). According to moderns views the first-mentioned 2 genera are now classified in groups that are widely remote of the 
<taxonomicName id="BB4AF140BD19977AAB41F55DA94225C7" class="Arachnida" family="Hypochthoniidae" genus="Hypochthoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Hypochthoniidae</taxonomicName>
, whilst 
<taxonomicName id="1C70337D61C0037FC081BBE5DB918BA8" class="Arachnida" family="Trizetidae" genus="Trizetes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Trizetes</taxonomicName>
even does not belong to the primitive Oribatid mites. The other ones are all reckoned among the 
<taxonomicName id="39F51C882988B6ED6E05BCCA0B123614" infraOrder="Enarthronota" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rank="infraOrder">Enarthronota</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8D1469FAA3F13E2687430C7AA131651F" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
3) In the same paper the name is, however, also spelt as 
<taxonomicName id="CFE389E9CFE4461EB6DB901883705DB8" family="Hypochthonidae" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rank="family">Hypochthonidae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9D0EB5A6BD6AD09FC9C185763187C8C0" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<pageBreakToken id="47709BBBF749CE692A56BBC6041CFE42" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" start="start">Nowadays</pageBreakToken>
the genera 
<taxonomicName id="FE05B31957F57E3D9AC233693DBDFCDB" class="Arachnida" family="Hypochthoniidae" genus="Hypochthonius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hypochthonius</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="F8763E93BA755312B280C8B600AED7F2" class="Arachnida" family="Hypochthoniidae" genus="Eohypochthonius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Eohypochthonius</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4E7D8AA7200C575118A945233A0DBC79" class="Arachnida" family="Hypochthoniidae" genus="Malacoangelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Malacoangelia</taxonomicName>
only are considered representatives of the family 
<taxonomicName id="F1F972162A7946FAC190FBA44F6AA6F1" class="Arachnida" family="Hypochthoniidae" genus="Hypochthoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Hypochthoniidae</taxonomicName>
1).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B223E4F54B4CDD36AB8500C37B718BB9" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
1) Recently Schweizer (1956, pp. 234-244, figs. 151-159) described a 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="6DD9068364B5257C643038DD380C6E65" rank="genus">new genus</taxonomicNameLabel>
<taxonomicName id="6CC9D265FB67F21B05955AA2157BBBF6" authority="Schweizer, 1956" authorityName="Schweizer" authorityYear="1956" class="Arachnida" family="Ceratozetidae" genus="Alphypochthonius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Oribatida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Alphypochthonius</taxonomicName>
with 9 new species, which he classified with the 
<taxonomicName id="5A39FD28D18F96A1654E461D513E0949" class="Arachnida" family="Hypochthoniidae" genus="Hypochthoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Hypochthoniidae</taxonomicName>
. All species are, however, nymphs and larvae of higher 
<taxonomicName id="1A5D37396EB43B31B7F8A4E7D8383652" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Oribatei</taxonomicName>
, probably 
<taxonomicName id="FA43A6E21D8E45C678A023E5B285199E" class="Arachnida" family="Ceratozetidae" genus="Melanozetes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Melanozetes</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="9D13A77BAB84232B153AD658F7951AB2" class="Arachnida" family="Ceratozetidae" genus="Fuscozetes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Fuscozetes</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="FDF638EC109CF6F2540E9F11B7BE9DF1" authority="Berlese, 1910" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1910" class="Arachnida" family="Ceratozetidae" genus="Trichoribates" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Oribatida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Trichoribates</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="6589130A592B3DDC186B2D2F1FCE8C0B" class="Arachnida" family="Ceratozetidae" genus="Sphaerozetes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Sphaerozetes</taxonomicName>
, etc. The type of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="DD1F9CF996941F730BBCE756F242BB0A" authority="Schweizer, 1956" authorityName="Schweizer" authorityYear="1956" class="Arachnida" family="Ceratozetidae" genus="Alphypochthonius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Oribatida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Alphypochthonius</taxonomicName>
is 
<taxonomicName id="3CDFAD70C422A3E5E7E64A50E2F80E27" authority="Schweizer, 1956" authorityName="Schweizer" authorityYear="1956" class="Arachnida" family="Ceratozetidae" genus="Alphypochthonius" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Oribatida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alpinus">A. alpinus</taxonomicName>
; description and figures of this species strongly resemble 
<taxonomicName id="31A83902CCEF430160038030A2906148" class="Arachnida" family="Ceratozetidae" genus="Melanozetes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Melanozetes</taxonomicName>
nymphs, probably 
<taxonomicName id="D7DC53501FE3817AE46A34DBA64A9530" class="Arachnida" family="Ceratozetidae" genus="Melanozetes" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mollicomus">M. mollicomus</taxonomicName>
(cf. Van der Hammen, 1952, p. 97, fig. 8d). 
<taxonomicName id="C7EC28317EC2914DBF10ED0FF987516D" authority="Schweizer, 1956" authorityName="Schweizer" authorityYear="1956" class="Arachnida" family="Ceratozetidae" genus="Alphypochthonius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Oribatida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Alphypochthonius</taxonomicName>
must therefore be placed in the synonymy of 
<taxonomicName id="B1C6D1D2F5582A6A453864D9A5D750F1" class="Arachnida" family="Ceratozetidae" genus="Melanozetes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Melanozetes</taxonomicName>
. I remark that the differences in measurements, which Schweizer regards as differences between males and females, are of course due to the presence of different nymphal stages.
</paragraph>
